<h2 id="key-features">⚙️ Key Features of Effective Retention Automation</h2>

Not all retention tools are created equal. After evaluating dozens of platforms, here are the features that separate systems that work from expensive notification spammers.

<h3>Behavioral Trigger Engine</h3>

The foundation of any retention system is its ability to detect meaningful behavior changes. Look for platforms that can trigger on:

- Days since last check-in (basic, but essential)
- Decline in visit frequency compared to member's own baseline
- Missed scheduled classes or appointments
- Failed payment attempts (often the first sign of intentional churn)
- Decreased app engagement
- Support ticket patterns

Kilo excels here by tracking over 40 behavioral signals and weighting them based on your gym's specific churn patterns. Their system learns which signals matter most for your member base, not just generic fitness industry benchmarks.

<h3>Multi-Channel Outreach Sequencing</h3>

Single-channel retention campaigns underperform dramatically. Your automation platform needs to orchestrate outreach across email, SMS, push notifications, and staff tasks in intelligent sequences.

A typical high-performing sequence might look like:
- Day 7 of inactivity: Push notification with personalized class recommendation
- Day 10: SMS from their usual trainer or coach
- Day 14: Email with value reminder and easy booking link
- Day 21: Staff task to make personal phone call
- Day 30: Win-back offer via SMS

Each step should suppress if the member takes action. Nobody wants four messages after they've already booked a class.

<h3>Dynamic Segmentation</h3>

Your longtime members need different retention approaches than someone three months in. First-year members churn at 3-4x the rate of members who've been with you two years or more. Your automation should segment accordingly.

Look for platforms that let you create segments based on:
- Membership tenure
- Membership type/tier
- Average visit frequency
- Lifetime value
- Acquisition source
- Location (for multi-site operators)

<h3>Integration Depth</h3>

Retention automation is only as good as the data feeding it. Your platform must integrate deeply with your access control system, class booking software, payment processor, and ideally your CRM.

Surface-level integrations that only sync member names and emails won't cut it. You need check-in timestamps, class attendance history, payment status, and ideally heart-rate or workout data if you're tracking it.

<h3>A/B Testing Infrastructure</h3>

What works for a 24-hour gym in Phoenix won't necessarily work for a boutique cycling studio in Boston. Your retention platform should allow you to test different message copy, timing, channels, and offers across segments.

Our team has seen retention message performance vary by 300% or more based on copy alone. "We haven't seen you in a while" performs dramatically worse than "Your favorite 6pm class has 3 spots left this Thursday."

